{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508019"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:00:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:00:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2705"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2705"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.08,0.01,0.37,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112965"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2705"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94996"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1046"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1175"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3382"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3383"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46479"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112965"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of acute confusion. Her family reports she has been not acting herself and has had intermittent hallucinations today. She also reports headache and recurrent epistaxis over the past two days, which are unusual for her. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She does not smoke or use alcohol, and works as a primary school teacher.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 112/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39.3\u00b0C. There are large ecchymoses over her thighs and arms without a history of trauma. Neurological examination shows normal power, tone, and reflexes in all limbs, but she intermittently has difficulty following commands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin: 82 g/L (115-165)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets: 12 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECreatinine: 180 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETotal bilirubin: 45 \u00b5mol/L (0-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELactate dehydrogenase: 890 U/L (120-250)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood film shows marked schistocytosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Corticosteroids","Empirical antibiotics","Endovascular coiling","Plasma exchange","Platelet transfusion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThrombotic thrombocytopaenic purpura is a life-threatening thrombotic microangiopathy caused by severe deficiency of ADAMTS13 activity, most often due to autoantibodies. Early recognition relies on the triad of microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia (schistocytes, raised lactate dehydrogenase, indirect hyperbilirubinaemia), thrombocytopaenia, and organ dysfunction (neurological signs, renal impairment, fever). The full historical pentad is uncommon because treatment is initiated earlier. Mortality is high without urgent therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma exchange\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial treatment. It removes anti-ADAMTS13 autoantibodies and replenishes ADAMTS13, rapidly improving platelet count and haemolysis. It should be commenced urgently on clinical suspicion without waiting for ADAMTS13 assay results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E are an important adjunct to suppress autoantibody production in immune-mediated thrombotic thrombocytopaenic purpura, but they are not definitive therapy and must not delay plasma exchange.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpirical antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not the priority here; fever can occur as part of thrombotic thrombocytopaenic purpura. While infections may trigger thrombotic thrombocytopaenic purpura, antibiotics do not address the underlying pathophysiology and should not delay plasma exchange.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndovascular coiling\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered for an intracranial aneurysm or active intracranial bleeding. The neurological features in this scenario are more consistent with microvascular ischaemia from thrombotic thrombocytopaenic purpura rather than a focal haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelet transfusion\u003C/strong\u003E is generally contraindicated because it may worsen microvascular thrombosis. It is reserved for life-threatening haemorrhage only, ideally after or during plasma exchange.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Thrombotic thrombocytopaenic purpura is a thrombotic microangiopathy with microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopaenia and organ dysfunction; the classic pentad is uncommon with early recognition.","Urgent plasma exchange is the key initial treatment for thrombotic thrombocytopaenic purpura and should not be delayed."],"references":["Joly BS, Coppo P, Veyradier A. Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura. Blood. 2017 May 25;129(21):2836\u201346. Available from: https://ashpublications.org/blood/article/129/21/2836/36273/Thrombotic-thrombocytopenic-purpura","Kremer Hovinga JA, Coppo P, L\u00e4mmle B, Moake JL, Miyata T, Vanhoorelbeke K. Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2017 Apr 6;3(1):1\u201317. Available from: https://www.nature.com/articles/nrdp201720"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94996"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2705"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94996"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T17:19:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T17:23:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2705"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112965"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","link